{"id":53901,"date":"2021-12-28T11:13:38","date_gmt":"2021-12-28T16:13:38","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/?p=53901"},"modified":"2025-04-17T15:54:27","modified_gmt":"2025-04-17T20:54:27","slug":"the-8-biggest-marketing-fails-of-all-time-with-practical-takeaways","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/blog\/ws\/2021\/12\/28\/marketing-fails","title":{"rendered":"The 8 Biggest Marketing Fails of All Time (With Practical Takeaways)"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>One marketing blunder can make or break any brand these days. Competition is fierce and if a brand doesn\u2019t (or accidentally doesn\u2019t appear to) align with a customers\u2019 values, there could be major consequences. In this post, we&#8217;re going to walk you through eight of the worst marketing fails in history by brands we&#8217;re familiar with. For each one, we&#8217;re going to cover:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>What the brand was trying to do<\/li>\n<li>Why it failed<\/li>\n<li>The key takeaway<\/li>\n<li>How to do it right<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>This way, you can walk away with practical ways to apply this to your small business or agency. Let\u2019s dive in.<\/p>\n<h2>8 major marketing fails and what they teach us<\/h2>\n<p>Something to keep in mind is that these marketing fails do not necessitate failure for any of these brands as a whole. None of them\u00a0would\u00a0be so famous if they didn&#8217;t have great marketing strategies. But the bigger you go, the bigger the results\u2014good or bad.<\/p>\n<div id=\"kendall-jenner-pepsi-ad\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#kendall-jenner-pepsi-ad\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>1.\u00a0Kendall Jenner Pepsi ad<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>This long commercial from 2017 follows along with a marching protest and features popular model Kendall Jenner watching and then joining it. In the end, she walks to the front of the protest line and hands a can of Pepsi to a police officer as a peace offering. He takes the Pepsi and everyone cheers.<em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=j9x15lR9VIg\"><\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>According to Pepsi, the ad was a move to promote global unity, peace, and understanding, but it achieved exactly the opposite. As soon as the ad came out, it received a storm of backlash and criticism. People found the ad insensitive and tone-deaf. Further, the ad supposedly trivialized the Black Lives Matter movement and made the protest seem like a fun party.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-pepsi-ad.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - kendall jenner pepsi ad\" width=\"720\" height=\"406\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53919\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-pepsi-ad.png 720w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-pepsi-ad-480x271.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<div data-embed-button=\"images\" data-entity-embed-display=\"view_mode:media.simple_image\" data-entity-type=\"media\" data-entity-uuid=\"bd23b315-f15a-4f68-beab-8a0ea94766b5\" data-langcode=\"en\" class=\"embedded-entity align-center\">\n<article>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=s_Ki4O3DpQQ\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Image source<\/em><\/a><\/p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https:\/\/www.nytimes.com\/2017\/04\/05\/business\/kendall-jenner-pepsi-ad.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">New York Times coverage<\/a> on the matter says it best:<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;Elle Hearns, the executive director of the Marsha P. Johnson Institute and formerly an organizer for Black Lives Matter, said the ad &#8216;plays down the sacrifices people have historically taken in utilizing protests. &#8216;No one is finding joy from Pepsi at a protest,\u201d she said. \u201cThat\u2019s just not the reality of our lives. That\u2019s not what it looks like to take bold action.\u201d<\/p>\n<p>Bernice King, the daughter of Martin Luther King Jr., was another of the activists who criticized the ad, tweeting &#8220;If only Daddy would have known about the power of #Pepsi.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-bernice-king-tweet-pepsi-ad.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - bernice king's response to pepsi ad\" width=\"500\" height=\"441\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53920\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-bernice-king-tweet-pepsi-ad.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-bernice-king-tweet-pepsi-ad-480x423.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/berniceking\/status\/849656699464056832?lang=en\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a> <\/em><\/p>\n<p>Pepsi pulled the ad from the air and YouTube within 24 hours and apologized saying the company \u201cmissed the mark.\u201d<\/p>\n<h3>The takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>Never use controversial topics or social issues to <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2020\/07\/29\/how-to-promote-a-product\">promote your products or services<\/a>. If you want to capitalize on a trending topic, do your research to make sure there is no risk for\u00a0polarizing\u00a0your audience and losing\u00a0customers.<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<p>If you want to leverage popular topics for marketing success,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Learn how to <a href=\"\/search-trends\">identify hot topics with search trend data<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Try out <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/03\/25\/social-listening-boolean-search\">social listening with boolean search.<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Know how to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.crewmarketingpartners.com\/insights\/tone-deaf-marketing\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">avoid tone-deaf marketing<\/a>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>\ud83d\udea8 <strong>Know what&#8217;s not a marketing fail? These ideas you can use all year long!<\/strong> Get the guide &gt;&gt; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/resources\/marketing-calendar?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_2025MarketingCalendar_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links\">The Mega Must-Have Marketing Calendar<\/a><\/p>\n<div id=\"gap-logo-redesign\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#gap-logo-redesign\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>2. Gap\u2019s logo redesign<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>In 2010, iconic brand Gap replaced its 20-year-old logo with a new one: black, bold font with a blue square in the upper right.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/biggest-marketing-fails-gap-logo-change.jpeg\" alt=\"biggest marketing fails - gap's logo change\" width=\"720\" height=\"246\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53902\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/biggest-marketing-fails-gap-logo-change.jpeg 720w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/biggest-marketing-fails-gap-logo-change-480x164.jpeg 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.thebrandingjournal.com\/2021\/04\/learnings-gap-logo-redesign-fail\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>According to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.vanityfair.com\/culture\/2010\/10\/new-gap-logo-despised-symbol-of-corporate-banality-dead-at-one-week\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">this Vanity Fair article<\/a>, it was Gap&#8217;s attempt to transition from \u201cclassic, American design to modern, sexy, cool,\u201d but it was immediately rejected by consumers, to the point of someone creating a satirical Gap logo Twitter feed, and yet another creating a site called &#8220;Crap Logo Yourself.&#8221; Gap tried to turn this into a &#8220;crowd sourcing project&#8221; with the below Facebook post, saying it is &#8220;thrilled to see passionate debates unfolding!&#8221; and asking followers to share their logo design ideas.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-gap-new-logo-twitter.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - new gap logo backlash on facebook\" width=\"500\" height=\"478\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53918\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-gap-new-logo-twitter.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-gap-new-logo-twitter-480x459.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/gap\/posts\/159977040694165\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Image source<\/em><\/a><\/p>\n<p>But this didn&#8217;t go over well, either.\u00a0\u00a0The backlash was so severe that the company switched back to its old logo within six days.<\/p>\n<h3>The takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>People like new things, but they also like tradition, so you have to strike a balance. If you&#8217;re going to make a major change in your branding, lower the risk of a negative response by getting outside input, interviewing or polling customers, testing it out on a small segment of your audience, or making a formal introduction addressing the change. And\u00a0always keep your most loyal customers at the forefront while making decisions. It is still possible to reach out to the new audience without losing the hearts of the old ones.<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<p>To keep your audience happy,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try any of these <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2014\/11\/10\/best-online-survey-tools\">free survey tools<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Learn how to create <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2015\/09\/23\/buyer-personas\">crazy-accurate buyer personas<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Follow these <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2016\/11\/10\/customer-loyalty\">loyalty marketing strategie<\/a>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>\ud83d\udd75\ufe0f\u200d\u2640\ufe0f <strong>Want to understand who you should be targeting with your marketing?<\/strong> Download the guide &gt;&gt; <a href=\"https:\/\/marketing.localiq.com\/WSLIQContentDLWebsiteTargetAudience.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_TargetAudineceGuide_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links\">How to Find Your Target Audience [Simple Steps!]<\/a><\/p>\n<div id=\"burger-king-women-day-tweet\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#burger-king-women-day-tweet\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>3. Burger King&#8217;s Women&#8217;s Day tweet<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>On International Womens Day in 2021, Burger King\u2019s UK division published a Twitter thread where the first tweet said: \u201cWomen belong in the kitchen\u201d and was followed by two more tweets, one that said &#8220;If they want to, of course&#8221; and another that announced their new scholarship program to help women get a degree in culinary arts and reduce the gender gap in the restaurant sector.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-uk-women-belong.jpeg\" alt=\"biggest marketing fails - burger king UKs sexist tweet\" width=\"720\" height=\"555\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53903\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-uk-women-belong.jpeg 720w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-uk-women-belong-480x370.jpeg 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Though the first tweet was intended to capture attention and the following two tweets\u00a0were progressive, many Twitter users never got past the first tweet, resulting in a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.usatoday.com\/story\/money\/2021\/03\/08\/burger-king-uk-under-fire-women-belong-kitchen-tweet\/4627505001\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">wave of backlash <\/a>for the seemingly sexist statement. And those who saw all three tweets still saw it as a tone-deaf attempt to honor Women&#8217;s Day.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-women-belong-twitter-response.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - responses to burger king's sexist tweet\" width=\"500\" height=\"546\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53904\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-women-belong-twitter-response.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-women-belong-twitter-response-480x524.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/BeccaBeckery\/status\/1368920951098929157?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1368920951098929157%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usatoday.com%2Fstory%2Fmoney%2F2021%2F03%2F08%2Fburger-king-uk-under-fire-women-belong-kitchen-tweet%2F4627505001%2F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Image source<\/em><\/a><\/p>\n<p>The chain deleted the thread and published a tweet apologizing for the mistake and explaining the intention.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-uk-apology-twitter.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - burger king's apology tweet\" width=\"500\" height=\"370\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53905\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-uk-apology-twitter.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-burger-king-uk-apology-twitter-480x355.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/BurgerKingUK\/status\/1369055736756600834?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1369055736756600834%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usatoday.com%2Fstory%2Fmoney%2F2021%2F03%2F08%2Fburger-king-uk-under-fire-women-belong-kitchen-tweet%2F4627505001%2F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<h3>The takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>Every social media platform works differently. What works on Instagram, where the user can see the big picture straight away, may not work over Twitter via single tweet. And what looks right on desktop could look entirely different on mobile. So test everything out before you hit publish, and as mentioned in the first example, don&#8217;t use something controversial to grab attention.\u00a0Customers might misinterpret your words. So, choose and present them wisely.<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<p>If you want to grab attention with your copywriting,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Try out these\u00a0<a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2017\/02\/13\/power-words-ad-writing\">power words and phrases<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Use <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/05\/03\/emotional-marketing-copy\">emotional trigger words<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Check these <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2014\/07\/17\/headline-writing\">tips for writing irresistible headlines.<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>\ud83d\udcda <strong>Free guide download &gt;&gt;<\/strong> <a href=\"https:\/\/marketing.wordstream.com\/WSLIQContentDLWebsite120WordsforMarketingWithEmotion.html?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_120WordsPhrases_Download\">135 of the Best Words &amp; Phrases for Marketing with Emotion<\/a><\/p>\n<div id=\"audi-wedding-commercial\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#audi-wedding-commercial\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>4. Audi\u2019s wedding commercial<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>In July of 2017, Audi aired a commercial where a bride and groom are about to take their vows, but the mother of the groom marches up to the alter and inspects the bride. She pinches her nose, pulls back her ear, and checks the inside of her mouth.<\/p>\n<p>The couple sighs in relief when she gives a nod of approval, but the mother gives one last look at the bride&#8217;s chest, which she covers anxiously with her hands.\u00a0The scene then changes to a red Audi sedan driving through the city streets\u00a0as a man\u2019s voice says\u00a0\u201can important decision must be made carefully.\u201d<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-audi-china-commercial-sexist.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails of all time - audi's sexist commercial\" width=\"720\" height=\"381\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53908\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-audi-china-commercial-sexist.png 720w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-audi-china-commercial-sexist-480x254.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=fM3HWnnWdkQ\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Image source<\/em><\/a><\/p>\n<p>The idea of Audi\u2019s campaign was to promote its properly-inspected\u00a0secondhand cars, but <a href=\"https:\/\/www.washingtonpost.com\/news\/worldviews\/wp\/2017\/07\/18\/an-audi-commercial-in-china-compared-women-to-used-cars-it-didnt-go-well\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">that is not how it was perceived.<\/a>\u00a0People all over the world\u00a0said that not only did it\u00a0objectify\u00a0women, but it also reduced their value to that of a vehicle.\u00a0Twitter users shared the commercial with comments like\u00a0\u201chow to make an ad that will turn off consumers,\u201d Weibo users criticized the ad as \u201cdisgusting,\u201d and\u00a0many people\u00a0urged a\u00a0boycott of the brand.<\/p>\n<p>Audi stated\u00a0it \u201cdeeply regrets\u201d the commercial\u2019s airing and that the ad \u201cdoes not correspond to the values of our company in any way.\u201d The ad, which was made exclusively for the Chinese audience, was withdrawn.<\/p>\n<h3>The takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>Just because you know the message behind your ad, this doesn&#8217;t mean everyone else will. Always run your content by a diverse group of people to make sure it&#8217;s 100% appropriate. And it goes without saying at this point, but\u00a0do not use controversial or potentially sensitive topics in your marketing campaigns.\u00a0If you have even a shadow of a doubt, don&#8217;t risk it.<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<p>If you want to create a bold and (positively) memorable marketing campaign,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Get inspiration from the <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/09\/28\/best-marketing-campaigns-examples\">five best marketing campaigns we&#8217;ve ever seen<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Establish your<a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/06\/09\/company-core-values\"> core values<\/a> and filter all of your content through them.<\/li>\n<li>Try these\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/blog\/ws\/2014\/09\/22\/guerrilla-marketing-examples\">guerrilla marketing ideas<\/a>\u00a0instead.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<div id=\"aairpass-by-american-airlines\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#aairpass-by-american-airlines\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>5. AAirpass by American Airlines<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>In the early 1980s, American Airlines was going through a rough patch and looking for quick ways to raise capital. Instead of securing bank loans, the company introduced an \u201cAAirpass\u201d that offered unlimited first-class air travel for a flat rate of $250,000.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-american-airlines-aairpass.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - american airlines aairpass\" width=\"500\" height=\"349\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53916\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-american-airlines-aairpass.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-american-airlines-aairpass-480x335.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.theguardian.com\/lifeandstyle\/2019\/sep\/19\/american-airlines-aairpass-golden-ticket\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>Unlike today when companies place restrictions on these kinds of offers to protect themselves from financial losses, the AAirpass was truly limitless and membership was life-long. The result? American Airlines started losing millions of dollars every year due to the high volume\u00a0of flights taken by AAirpass holders. It started an investigation to see whether there was any way they could revoke the membership of the frequent flyers, resulting in outrage and lawsuits.<\/p>\n<p>In a nutshell, American Airlines\u2019 strategy to make quick money backfired, resulting in financial losses and angry customers.<\/p>\n<h3>Takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>If you\u2019re offering a high-value incentive to your customers, include terms and conditions\u00a0to protect your business\u00a0from exploitation and make sure the cost of the incentive does not (or will not eventually)\u00a0outweigh the benefits to your business. And remember, there is no such thing as fast money in business! It takes careful planning and a holistic strategy.<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<p>If you want to stay financially sound,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Find out\u00a0<a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/10\/12\/growth-marketing\">what growth marketing really means and 22 strategies to get it right<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Use these simpler <a href=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/blog\/ws\/2020\/11\/02\/promote-your-business\">ways to promote your business\u2014with or without money<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Focus on <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2016\/10\/04\/adwords-roi\">maximizing ROI<\/a>\u00a0and plugging leaks in your spend.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/google-adwords?cid=Web_blog_InContentTextLink\"><strong><em>Are you wasting any money in Google Ads? Find out with the FREE Google Ads Performance Grader!<\/em><\/strong><\/a><\/p>\n<div id=\"bloomingdales-spiked-eggnog-ad\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#bloomingdales-spiked-eggnog-ad\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>6. Bloomingdales&#8217; spiked eggnog ad<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>In their 2015\u00a0Christmas catalog, Bloomingdale&#8217;s\u00a0published an ad showing a sharply dressed man staring at a laughing woman who has her head turned, and a caption that\u00a0read, &#8220;Spike your best friend&#8217;s eggnog when they&#8217;re not looking.\u201d<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-eggnog-ad.jpeg\" alt=\"worst marketing fails of all time - bloomingdales' magazine ad\" width=\"720\" height=\"421\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53909\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-eggnog-ad.jpeg 720w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-eggnog-ad-480x281.jpeg 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.huffpost.com\/entry\/bloomingdales-apologizes-for-super-creepy-holiday-ad_n_56438b84e4b0603773475769\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<div>The ad caused outrage as it seemed to encourage date rape. People responded with tweets saying things like &#8220;Unbelievable that Bloomingdale&#8217;s date rape ad is real,&#8221; and\u00a0 &#8220;Fascinated that throughout the editing process, nobody suggested this Christmas ad is a bad idea.&#8221;<\/div>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-twitter-response.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails of all time - bloomingdales magazine ad, twitter response\" width=\"500\" height=\"428\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53910\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-twitter-response.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-twitter-response-480x411.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/DrRobson\/status\/664466157617958912?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E664466157617958912%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fmedia%2F2015%2Fnov%2F11%2Fbloomingdales-apologizes-holiday-ad-date-rape-joke\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>In response to the uproar, Bloomingdale&#8217;s tweeted an apology, calling the ad &#8220;inappropriate and in poor taste.\u201d<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-apology.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - bloomingdales' apology tweet\" width=\"500\" height=\"217\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53911\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-apology.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-bloomingdales-apology-480x208.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/Bloomingdales\/status\/664216552544165888?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E664216552544165888%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.huffpost.com%2Fentry%2Fbloomingdales-apologizes-for-super-creepy-holiday-ad_n_56438b84e4b0603773475769\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>However, this was a print ad, so there was no way to pull it from already distributed catalogs.<\/p>\n<h3>Takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>Playful humor is a good way to engage your audience, but never take this chance with controversial and sensitive topics. Furthermore, be extra cautious with printed material. You can delete a social media post or stop running a digital ad (although yes, there will be screenshots), but it&#8217;s much harder to take back printed material, or detect the negative reactions quickly.<\/p>\n<h3>Tools<\/h3>\n<p>If you want to have fun with your holiday content,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Learn <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2014\/09\/10\/comedy-in-content-marketing\">how to use humor in marketing the right way<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Get inspired by these <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2013\/10\/08\/funny-ads\">funny ads that work<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Take a look at these <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/11\/01\/holiday-copywriting\">genius tips and examples for fun and cliche-free holiday copywriting<\/a>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<div id=\"dove-racist-campaign\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#dove-racist-campaign\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>7. Dove\u2019s \u2018racist\u2019 campaign<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>In 2017, Dove posted a three-second video on Facebook of three women of different ethnicities, each removing a t-shirt to reveal the next woman. The intention was to celebrate diversity and convey that its body wash is for every woman.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-racist-ad.jpeg\" alt=\"worst marketing fails of all time - dove's racist ad\" width=\"720\" height=\"330\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53912\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-racist-ad.jpeg 720w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-racist-ad-480x220.jpeg 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/scroll.in\/article\/853618\/doves-tone-deaf-advertisement-and-the-racist-history-of-skin-whitening\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>However, it was perceived as a black woman transforming into a white woman after using the body wash, implying that the black woman was less clean than the white woman. The ad was called\u00a0inappropriate and racist, and many consumers responded by boycotting Dove products altogether.<\/p>\n<p>Dove quickly removed the post and tweeted an immediate apology, saying it &#8220;missed the mark in representing women of color thoughtfully.&#8221;<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-apology-tweet.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails of all time - dove's apology tweet\" width=\"500\" height=\"262\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53913\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-apology-tweet.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-apology-tweet-480x252.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/Dove\/status\/916731793927278592?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E916731793927278592%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.inc.com%2Fsonia-thompson%2Fthis-dove-ad-made-me-cry-for-all-wrong-reasons-heres-what-brands-can-learn-from-it.html\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>It later published a more thorough statement that explained the intent of the ad, reaffirmed Dove&#8217;s core beliefs, and ensured it would be re-evaluating its internal processes to prevent this mistake in the future.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-apology-on-twitter.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - dove's apology tweet\" width=\"500\" height=\"334\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53914\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-apology-on-twitter.png 500w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/worst-marketing-fails-dove-apology-on-twitter-480x321.png 480w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/Dove\/status\/917444642047778816?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E917444642047778816%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fscroll.in%2Farticle%2F853618%2Fdoves-tone-deaf-advertisement-and-the-racist-history-of-skin-whitening\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Image source<\/em><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>Takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>While diversity\u00a0is sensitive topic, it is one we are held responsible to demonstrate and celebrate\u00a0through our marketing. This should just be a standard for all of our content, but if you are going to make an extra push, make sure to run it by as many people as possible before you go live. Better yet, make sure to hire people of diverse background\u00a0so you can have a built-in, multi-perspective review team.<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<h4>If you want to succeed with a cause-related marketing campaign,<\/h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Learn how to\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/localiq.com\/blog\/growth-lab\/4-tactics-cultivating-diversity-your-workforce\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">cultivate\u00a0a diverse workforce<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Make sure you know how to\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/blog\/ws\/2021\/04\/28\/diversity-in-marketing\">demonstrate true diversity in marketing<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Check out our tips on <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2018\/02\/22\/cause-based-marketing\">cause-based marketing<\/a>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<div id=\"coca-cola-new-coke\"><a class=\"subhead-anchor\" rel=\"#coca-cola-new-coke\"><svg width=\"19\" height=\"19\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 14\"><g fill=\"none\" fill-rule=\"evenodd\"><path d=\"M0 0h14v14H0z\"><\/path><path d=\"M7.45 9.887l-1.62 1.621c-.92.92-2.418.92-3.338 0a2.364 2.364 0 0 1 0-3.339l1.62-1.62-1.273-1.272-1.62 1.62a4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.885 5.884l1.62-1.62L7.45 9.886zM5.527 5.135L7.17 3.492c.92-.92 2.418-.92 3.339 0 .92.92.92 2.418 0 3.339L8.866 8.473l1.272 1.273 1.644-1.643A4.161 4.161 0 1 0 5.897 2.22L4.254 3.863l1.272 1.272zm-.66 3.998a.749.749 0 0 1 0-1.06l2.208-2.206a.749.749 0 1 1 1.06 1.06L5.928 9.133a.75.75 0 0 1-1.061 0z\"><\/path><\/g><\/svg><\/a><\/p>\n<h3>8. Coca-Cola\u2019s \u2018New Coke\u2019 Flavor<\/h3>\n<\/div>\n<p>In the 1980s, the war between Pepsi and Coca-Cola\u00a0was at its peak. Though Coca-Cola was number one, Pepsi had been closing the gap with brilliant ad campaigns like the <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pepsi_Challenge\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Pepsi Challenge<\/a>\u00a0in 1975.<\/p>\n<p>To get back in the game, Coca-Cola introduced &#8220;New Coke,\u201d on April 23, 1985\u2014which had the smooth and sweeter taste of Diet Coke, but sweetened with corn syrup. Coca-Cola had tested it on 200,000 subjects and<a href=\"https:\/\/www.business2community.com\/consumer-marketing\/market-research-fail-new-coke-became-worst-flub-time-01256904\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> 53% <\/a>preferred the New Coke recipe over the original. However, when it finally went to market, customers hated it.<\/p>\n<p><img decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-new-coke.png\" alt=\"worst marketing fails - new coke\" width=\"400\" height=\"402\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-53917\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-new-coke.png 400w, https:\/\/www.wordstream.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/12\/marketing-fails-new-coke-150x150.png 150w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px\" \/><\/p>\n<p class=\"text-align-center\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><a href=\"https:\/\/www.coca-colacompany.com\/company\/history\/the-story-of-one-of-the-most-memorable-marketing-blunders-ever\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Image source<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<p>Coca-Cola received 400,000 phone calls and letters from angry consumers professing their dissatisfaction with the new flavor. Coke returned its original formula &#8220;Coca-Cola Classic&#8221; to the shelves in the wake of the backlash.<\/p>\n<h3>Takeaway<\/h3>\n<p>Coca-Cola clearly did more market research than Gap, but the takeaway here is that taste alone is not the only factor in your customers&#8217; satisfaction.\u00a0Coca-Cola&#8217;s\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/localiq.com\/blog\/how-to-create-a-brand-identity\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">brand identity<\/a>\u00a0has been closely tied to friendship and nostalgia, and this new recipe did not align with that. Always consider what your products mean to your customers on an emotional level. Also,\u00a0when you have a successful product, be cautious about upgrades\u00a0and improvements.\u00a0If it ain&#8217;t broke, don&#8217;t fix it!<\/p>\n<h3>How to do it right<\/h3>\n<p>If you want to launch a new product or gain an edge over your competitors,<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Learn from\u00a0<a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2019\/08\/26\/competitive-ads\">the best competitive ads we&#8217;ve ever seen<\/a>.<\/li>\n<li>Follow these <a href=\"https:\/\/localiq.com\/blog\/how-to-build-a-go-to-market-strategy\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">steps to build a solid go-to-market strategy<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Make sure you have a <a href=\"\/blog\/ws\/2021\/02\/01\/brand-strategy\">solid brand strategy<\/a>\u00a0in place.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/localiq.com\/localiq-grader?utm_source=wordstream&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=freemium\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><strong><em>Find out how your online presence stacks up against your competitors with the free LOCALiQ Online Presence Grader.<\/em><\/strong><\/a><\/p>\n<h2>Marketing fails are in the details<\/h2>\n<p>Every business wants to stand out, but unless you take your time and fully think through your ideas and plans, you run the risk of going\u00a0viral for the wrong reasons. Whether you&#8217;re a massive brand or a local shop, the biggest takeaway here is the same: <strong>Pay attention to the details\u2014<\/strong>in how you present your message, represent your values, plan your campaigns, and if (hopefully not) applicable, how you apologize.<\/p>\n<h3>About the author<\/h3>\n<p>Dhruv Maheshwari is the founder of <a href=\"https:\/\/outsourc.io\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Outsourc<\/a>. He helps brands grow organically through winning content, and in his free time, he is chiseling his fitness goals and traveling around the world.<\/p>\n<\/article>\n<\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Be prepared for more than just marketing takeaways. This one&#8217;s an eye-opener.<\/p>\n"